04230nam a22005415i 9780691235738DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2022060358  a97806912357387 a10.1515/97806912357382doi  a(DE-B1597)658552  a(OCoLC)1371485249  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aHV741 7aSOC0250002bisacsh04a362.70973223//eng/20230227eng1 aFong, Kelley, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aInvestigating Families :bMotherhood in the Shadow of Child Protective Services /cKelley Fong. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b2 b/w illus. 1 table.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1 The Specter of the State -- t2 Making the Call -- t3 Fear and Surveillance in the Investigation -- t4 From Needs to Risks -- t5 Here to Help? -- t6 Devastation and Demobilization Beyond the Investigation -- tConclusion -- tMethodological Appendix -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tA Note on the Type0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow our reliance on Child Protective Services makes motherhood precarious for those already marginalizedIt’s the knock on the door that many mothers fear: a visit from Child Protective Services (CPS), the state agency with the power to take their children away. Over the last half-century, these encounters have become an all-too-common way of trying to address family poverty and adversity. One in three children nationwide—and half of Black children—now encounter CPS during childhood.In Investigating Families, Kelley Fong provides an unprecedented look at the inner workings of CPS and the experiences of families pulled into its orbit. Drawing on firsthand observations of CPS investigations and hundreds of interviews with those involved, Fong traces the implications of invoking CPS as a “first responder” to family misfortune and hardship. She shows how relying on CPS—an entity fundamentally oriented around parental wrongdoing and empowered to separate families—organizes the response to adversity around surveilling, assessing, and correcting marginalized mothers. The agency’s far-reaching investigative apparatus undermines mothers’ sense of security and shapes how they marshal resources for their families, reinforcing existing inequalities. And even before CPS comes knocking, mothers feel vulnerable to a system that jeopardizes their parenthood. Countering the usual narratives of punitive villains and hapless victims, Fong’s unique, behind-the-scenes account tells a revealing story of how we try to protect children by threatening mothers—and points the way to a more productive path for families facing adversity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChild abusezUnited StatesxPrevention. 0aChild welfarezUnited States. 0aChildrenxServices forzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Work.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311074974840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691235738?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691235738423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691235738/original  a978-3-11-074974-8  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles